ts where residents interacted with individuals of other races and cultures. In fact, as his engaging account makes clear, between 1900 and 1940 such multiethnic areas mushroomed in Los Angeles. Street Meeting, enriched with oral histories, reminiscences, newspaper reports, and other sources, examines interactions among working-class Mexicans, Chinese, Japanese, Jews, Italians, African Americans, and others, reminding us that Los Angeles has been a multiethnic city since its birth. This study further argues that these ethnic interactions played a crucial role in the urban development of the United States during the early decades of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnic neighborhoodszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american culture.  a20th century american history.  a20th century american society.  aafrican americans.  aamerican history.  acalifornia.  achinese americans.  acity life.  acommunist party.  acorporate reconstruction.  acrowded cities.  acultural studies.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration and emigration.  aindigenous immigrant communities.  aitalian americans.  ajewish americans.  alos angeles.  amarriage.  amexican americans.  amultiethnic communities.  arace in america.  aunited states of america.  aurban development.  aurbanization.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024083440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094176240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520941762/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEB